Privates on Parade was the making of me
The death of rep makes it more difficult for actors to learn their craft, but talent will out Dramatic pause: many of our greatest actors learnt their craft in repertory theatre Photo: Rex Features	By Michael Simkins
7:35PM GMT 15 Nov 2012
Comments
Sir Ian McKellen’s lament about the demise of repertory theatre, and his stark warning about how today’s fragmented, celebrity-obsessed industry is in danger of failing the next generation of leading actors on whom theatre tradition relies, may have caused bemusement among the younger generation of aspiring stars. If so, I suspect it’s only because many of them won’t have a clue what repertory is.
When I left Rada in the mid-Seventies there were still 70 or 80 regional reps you could apply to for a thorough training in stagecraft: Derby, Lancaster, Farnham – their names read like some theatrical Bradshaw. Back then you were assured of at least half a dozen sequential productions if you landed the job, with parts ranging from juvenile leads to the back end of a pantomime cow. Time to learn, to observe, to find your feet and, crucially, to sort your emotions and your technique out before things got serious in the West End or on TV.
My second job at the Theatre Royal York in 1979 perfectly reflected the extraordinary and nourishing training ground that only repertory could provide. My 12-month contract started with a production of Pinero’s classic farce The Magistrate, followed by Shakespeare’s The Taming of the Shrew, on through Alan Ayckbourn’s Bedroom Farce, and then to Trevor Griffiths’s savage indictment of culture in Seventies Britain, Comedians, about a group of aspiring stand-ups attending evening classes in deepest Manchester.
In the role of Eddie Waters, the club comic who is their weekly instructor, the director cast the popular local stand-up Stan Richards (later to achieve immortality as Seth Armstrong in Emmerdale Farm). During rehearsals the entire cast even went over to Bradford Working Men’s Club to see Stan perform his shtick in front of a packed Sunday night crowd. (“My dog has no legs – I call it Marlboro ’cos every night I take it out for a drag.”) It was exotic, wonderful stuff.
But even after that the season was barely half-way through. I played a one-line reporter in Ben Travers’s Thark, then Tony Lumpkin in She Stoops To Conquer, then the lead in a new play written about the recently discovered Viking remains in the centre of the city, before high-kicking my way through Peter Nichols’s musical Privates on Parade, about a group of soldiers touring with the Combined Services Entertainment Unit in darkest Malaya.
