The season finished – as all good rep seasons have to – with pantomime; in my case, Dick Whittington and His Cat, starring (in his first leading role) a young Gary Oldman as Cat. Unable to return home for Christmas due to heavy snow, I ended up squeezing into a single bed with him at a house in Rotherham owned by the parents of the actor playing the Sultan of Morocco.
Some of my casting, was, perforce, preposterous (my 60-year-old police sergeant, in particular, springs to mind). But the experience it offered was priceless. I learnt how to time a laugh, to hold a pause, and to know the difference between an audience of 80 at a Thursday matinee and a full house on a Saturday night. Most importantly, I experienced a crash course in nearly 400 years of British drama.
It also gave me the chance to act with, and learn from, leading actors who themselves had been schooled in this peerless tradition. Their names now seem as yellowing and forgotten as their photographs, invariably hanging in tatty frames in the parlours of the legions of theatrical landladies who looked after them (many of whom became surrogate mothers, nursemaids, and even lovers). Watching these theatrical titans taught me more than a decade at drama school ever could.
Nobody, least of all me, is advocating a return to the days when every town and city had its own company. Many of the smaller reps were threadbare even by the Seventies, and deserved to go to the wall: but the majority were strong, robust and exciting enterprises, with high production values, exacting standards and, crucially, with a real sense of belonging among the community in which they resided.
Perhaps Sir Ian’s anxieties about whether the next generation of Gambons, Denches and indeed McKellens will ever find the opportunity to discover their profound talent are premature. Talent, I suspect, will always out. But if so, their path is likely to be far more tortuous than that enjoyed by their predecessors.
Is it possible that I, too, could be merely peering back at these heady, far-off days through rose-tinted spectacles? Maybe – but if so, I’m in good company. Meeting Gary Oldman unexpectedly on Hungerford Bridge a few years ago, we stopped briefly to recall our days together, nearly four decades before. “Simmo,” he concluded, “I’m a movie star, I live in LA, I’ve had everything the business could offer me. But there are times when I’d throw it all away, just for one week back doing Privates on Parade at York.”
Oldman, is of course, one of our finest actors – but I’d like to think that on this occasion, he was telling the truth.
