Who will David Cameron listen to on building in the countryside?
It was remarkable that Nadhim Zahawi, Conservative MP for Stratford-upon-Avon and member of the No 10 policy board, decided to attack the National Planning Policy Framework Prime Minister David Cameron with members of his advisory board on policy Photo: Getty Images	By Isabel Hardman
8:41PM GMT 09 Jan 2014
Follow Comments
A Conservative MP complaining about the Government’s planning reforms is hardly as rare as hen’s teeth these days. Grumbles about what many MPs fear is a free-for-all that favours developers form a low-level backing track to Tory party life. But it was still remarkable when Nadhim Zahawi, the MP for Stratford-upon-Avon, decided to attack the National Planning Policy Framework this week. Mr Zahawi was simply repeating what many colleagues feel when he said the reforms were causing “physical harm” and “pain” to the countryside. His intervention was significant, though, because he is a member of the No 10 policy board – and he has now been told in no uncertain terms to support the planning reforms or resign. Initially, Tory MPs were encouraged that someone on this supposedly influential panel of MPs, helping the Prime Minister develop election-winning ideas, was prepared to speak up on planning. Mr Zahawi isn’t so encouraging, however. “This has nothing to do with the policy board,” he says. “I was speaking in my capacity as Stratford-upon-Avon’s MP.” He does not plan to raise it with the unit. And neither does the No 10 hierarchy plan to listen. There is clearly considerable frustration in Downing Street that Mr Zahawi has spoken out of turn only a few months after being appointed to the board. He and his fellow new members – Alun Cairns, Andrea Leadsom, Priti Patel and Chris Skidmore – had already been warned that, although they were not ministers, they were signing up to agree with Government policy. The reason the powers-that-be at No 10 took such care to state this was that they had only recently removed one of the board’s best-known members, Jesse Norman. The MP for Hereford and South Herefordshire had failed to turn up to the vote on Syria because he disagreed with military intervention. But the excitement about Mr Zahawi’s comments is a symptom of a bigger problem. This is that the purportedly “influential” policy board is not, in fact, influential at all. When it was set up in April 2013, it was a gesture from David Cameron to his party, to say that old wounds such as revolts over Europe and Lords reform should be left to heal. It was also a useful way of keeping MPs who had missed out on a promotion busy, happy and distracted from potential rebellions. And so the policy board was sold as a rather more exciting entity than it really is. It is simply a conduit between the back benches and the PM. Anyone who really works on policy in No 10 says that it’s entirely wrong to assume this group will have much to do with writing the 2015 manifesto. Jo Johnson, the head of the board, will be involved, but not the members. Mr Johnson runs the unit with an impressive iron discipline. He has put the fear of God into members over briefing the media about any idea they are working on (although Mr Zahawi seems considerably more relaxed about this than the other nine members). What has trickled out so far has hardly been game-changing: indeed, it is amusing that only the Stratford MP’s freelance outbursts have made it on to the front pages. Ministers, meanwhile, are unperturbed by its activities, preferring instead to fret about how much access Oliver Letwin is being given to the making of the manifesto (not a lot, at present). Related Articles
MP faces 'peasants in revolt’ over his mother’s plan to build homes
05 Jan 2014
Policy wonk who wants to build 1.5milion new homes and a garden city is David Cameron's new planning adviser
10 Dec 2013
Councils in popular areas should build more homes to stop house prices rising, Nick Boles says
10 Dec 2013
Home builders to get £1bn loans to start work in town centres
05 Dec 2013
We may hear less from Mr Zahawi if his colleagues succeed in threatening him into submission. But his was never an outburst that could change either Government or Tory policy. It is far more interesting that the Prime Minister has recently appointed Policy Exchange’s Alex Morton as his planning and housing adviser. Morton is a passionate advocate of increased housebuilding, but in a way that does not antagonise local communities. It will be his work, and that of advisers we never hear from, that exerts real sway over future policy. And if the No 10 board has so little actual influence, why should Mr Cameron worry what its members say? Planning
